    <Point><coordinates>-97.126969,33.630711,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Nelson Grove Cemetery</name>
    <description><![CDATA[9 miles east of Gainesville on US 82, then 1.5 miles south on FM 678<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> Gainesville<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> In 1875 Mollie Nelson, the 14-year-old daughter of Robert Carroll and Mary Elizabeth Nelson, died of pneumonia and measles and was buried on her parents' property. Two years later, R C. Nelson and J. C. Stockton deeded land including Mollie's grave site to the Cooke County judge for use as a "school, church and burying ground." The Nelson Grove School provided an education for neighboring families until 1924, and funeral services often were held in the schoolhouse. A cemetery association founded in 1964 cares for the graveyard and has held an annual Memorial Day meeting since 1970. At the turn of the 21st century, there were more than 800 burials in the cemetery. (2000) Historic Texas Cemetery - 2008]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-97.010196,33.633466,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Oak Grove Community</name>
    <description><![CDATA[7 mi. E on FM 678, 0.3 mi. S on CR 219<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> Gainesville<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> In the 1860s, George Sanford Norrid left his Missouri home with his wife, Tabitha, and family and moved to Texas, settling in this area and offering their home for church services. In 1875, F.M. Dougherty and George Norrid deeded land for a Methodist Epsicopal church; Norrid's donation preserved land for a cemetery. When Tabitha Norrid died in January 1876, she was the first buried in what became the Oak Grove Cemetery. Area families used the church building for school and worship until 1884, when they moved the building, and with it the school and church, to nearby Woodbine. The Methodist church later deeded its land to the cemetery association, which maintains the burial ground. (2005)]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-97.036622,33.60717,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Sivells Bend United Methodist Church</name>
    <description><![CDATA[CR 437 at FM1201<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> Sivells Bend<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> This congregation formed in 1868 as Sivells Bend Methodist Episcopal Church, South. Brothers William W. and Addison Y. Gunter conveyed two acres to church trustees E. L. Allen, WM. Midkiff and George Dillard in 1880. A large two-story church, school and masonic lodge burned in 1893. W. W. Gunter deeded the current site in 1910. The present frame church has had continuous services since its 1912 construction. During WWII, families taught Sunday school even without a supplied pastor. Later, Sivells Bend shared pastors with other Methodist churches, but has had its own pastors since 1950. Community involvement and regular worship shows a continuing focus on the true spirit of God.]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-97.230401,33.843868,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Van Slyke Cemetery</name>
    <description><![CDATA[N on FM 1199, W on CR 446, N on CR 453, 5 mi. NW of Lindsay<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> Lindsay<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Van Slyke Cemetery Established 1883 Historic Texas Cemetery - 2005]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-97.277133,33.695378,0</coordinates></Point>
